04145nam a22005655i 9780773548398DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20162016xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807735483987 a10.1515/97807735483982doi  a(DE-B1597)656665  a(OCoLC)952211051  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 7aHIS0060002bisacsh04a971.8/20209222300aGeorge Cartwright's The Labrador Companion /ced. by Marianne P. Stopp. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2016] 4c©2016  a1 online resource :b55 photos  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tPreface -- tIntroduction -- tTable 1 Entries from The Labrador Companion in order of Cartwright’s page numbers -- tAppendix -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aNew manuscripts directly related to Canada’s history rarely come to light. The Labrador Companion, written in 1810 by Captain George Cartwright (1739-1819), and discovered in 2013, is a fascinating and unusual find because of its level of detail, its setting in a hardly studied part of Britain’s fur-trade empire, and because it is a personal account rather than a trade outfit ledger or government document. This annotated edition transcribes The Labrador Companion in full. Cartwright documented the everyday work of Labrador’s particular kind of fur-trade life based on his experiences operating a series of merchant stations in southern Labrador between 1770 and 1786. Although his focus is firmly on instruction in the manifold ways of capturing animals, he also provides rare glimpses of Innu and Inuit life as well as of housekeeping and gardening. The Labrador Companion includes a lengthy description of Labrador’s fauna – of land, sea, and air – that counts among Canada’s earliest natural history writing based on first-hand observation. A revealing account of fur-trade-era technology, methods, and materials, conveyed through one man’s acquired knowledge and skills, The Labrador Companion gives a close-to-the-ground picture of the resource industries that were at the heart of British, and French, colonial presence in the Canadian northeast.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aFrontier and pioneer lifezNewfoundland and LabradorzLabrador. 0aFur tradezNewfoundland and LabradorzLabradorxHistoryy18th century. 0aFur traderszNewfoundland and LabradorzLabradorxHistoryy18th century. 0aHuntingzNewfoundland and LabradorzLabradorxHistoryy18th century. 0aInuitzNewfoundland and LabradorzLabradorxHistoryy18th century. 0aNatural historyzNewfoundland and LabradorzLabrador. 7aHISTORY / Canada / General.2bisacsh1 aStopp, Marianne P., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311127380808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2016z978311127630440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780773548398?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780773548398423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780773548398/original  a978-3-11-127380-8  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  a978-3-11-127630-4  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2016b2016  aGBV-deGruyter-alles